Hurricanes good cause for insanity

Ever wanted to go wild on national
television?

Well, here’s your chance. Tonight, the
Pittsburgh Panthers face the 
Hurricanes at Heinz Field._

Four years ago, the Panthers upset the
Hunicanes 21-17 in a Thursday night game
at Pitt Stadium.

That night, campus went wild. A mob
of students rushed the ﬁeld, tore down the
goalpost and tossed it over the tall end of
Pitt Stadium. 0

Except for games against Penn State,

we haven’t seen that kind of school spirit -

since. Tonight is the time to change that.

ESPN will broadcast the game live
nationwide. Our last game made national
headlines — because South Florida had only
beaten one other Division I-A team — so
tonight is our chance for redemption.’

It is our hope that the upset three weeks
ago will help the Panthers begin anew. Even
if they don’t beat the N o. 1 Hurricanes, they
could at least show a respectable perfor-
mance. After our humiliation against South
Florida, we still got four votes in the
ESPN/U SA Today ‘poll. After tonight, those
votes will either grow or vanish.

But the Panthers can’t do it without the
12th Man.

How many schools get to be on nation-
al television on a Thursday night? Tonight
is our chance to show how enthused Pitt
studentsreally are. .

Get wild on campus before the game.
Get wild on the buses. Get wild in the sta-

dium. .

Whenever the camera focuses on the
student section, viewers from Anchorage to
Miami should see a rowdy crowd. They
should see no one sitting. They should see
students yelling and cheering for their
Panthers. They should see signs all over.

The stadium should be so loud that the
folks at home can hear us better than they
hear the commentators. They should also
hear us chanting whatever we want — who
cares what the administration says or what
the band plays.

This is possibly the event of the semes-
ter at Pitt. It’s a Thursday night game. It’s
against the No. 1 team in the country.

And the game is going to have a patri-
otic pre-game show. Lee Greenwood will
sing his most famous song, “God Bless the
U.S.A. (Proud to Be an American),” and
We’re going to have the world’s biggest
American ﬂag on the ﬁeld again. ,

We have no excuse not to be there.
Many professors have cancelled classes and
even tests. -

And tonightwill-be a great timeto s
some glory of Pitt past. We’re retiring Mark
May’s number, and anyone else with that
honor — including Mike Ditka and Dan
Marino — will be there.

I.et’s show the country that We’re not
apathetic. Let’s go wild on national televi-
sion. *

And who knows, maybe when it’s all
over we’ll have blown away the
Hurricanes.

