An open letter to
Chancellor Nordenberg

Tonight is the start of the Jewish

‘holiday Yom Kippur. The holiday

begins at sundown, around 7 p.m.
tonight, and ends at sundown, again
around 7 p.m., tomorrow night.
Yom Kippur is the holiest and
most solemn day of the Jewish year.
Qn Yom Kippur, Jews fast for 25
hours and repent to God to forgive
us of our sins we committed over the
last year. We fast in order to show
how sorry we are for committing
these sins. We also don’t watch tele-
vision, write or do any other kind of

I work throughout the 25 hours.

This ensures Jewish people that
they are strictly thinking about
repenting to God. Tonight at 7,
while I will be praying in syna-
gogue, the University has scheduled
its annual bonfire. Why tonight? I
am a sophomore at Pitt and I greatly
enjoyed going to the bonfire last
year. I really had a lot of fun. This
year I’m unable to attend because of
my religion. I don’t understand why
the bonfire isn’t on homecoming
week.

Also, it’s unfortunate that
Jewish people have to miss classes
on Thursday. And, for me personal-
1y, I have to break my fast early for
the Pitt football game Thursday
night.

I announce football games on
WPTS-FM. This game is my time to
shine and announce a game for the
No. 1 team in the country. There are

more than 3,000 Jewish students at

the University of Pittsburgh, and
many more Jewish alumni. For all
Jewish people, it is not considerate
of the NCAA and Pitt to make a
bonfire or a football game on the
holiest day of the Jewish year.

I’m aware that there isn’t any-
thing that can be done for tonight’s
bonfire and tomorrow’s game, but
since I am only a sophomore, I
would like to see this never happen
again. Thank you.

Brian Goldman
University of Pittsburgh Hillel
Treasurer

