did Sept. 16, 1926.

Though there is no ‘hurricane
mascot, Miami does have Sebastian
the Ibis, one -of the nation’s most
recognized mascots. Story has it
that in 1926 the school’s yearbook
adopted the name “Ibis” after the
local marsh bird. A

The name’s popularity grew and
in 1957 a residence building on
campus called San Sebastian Hall
sponsored an Ibis entry in. the

' homecoming celebration. The next

year student John Stormont per:
formed at games in a homemade
‘Ibis outfit and the mascot stuck.
When Miami takes the field in
the Orange Bowl they have one of
the nation’s most famous entrances.
The “Smoke” entrance as it is com-

'monly referred to started in the-

1950s.

Hurricane players storm the
field through a thick cloud of
“smoke” that is actually made from
fire extinguishers before every
game while the sounds of a hurri-
cane play over the stadium’s sound
system. The original set up
alsoiincluded ﬂashing lights and

‘ two large hurricane ﬂags blowing

in the wind, but they fell to the
Wayside for today’s “smoke” and
wind sound entrance. , '

Miami also has ‘a few lesser

I known charms that add to a game in.

the Orange Bowl, including .‘-‘Lil’
Joe” and “Touchdown Tommy.”
“Lil’ Joe?’ was the predecessor to
the current “Touchdown Tommy”
cannon that is fired by the Sigma
Chi fraternity after each Miami
score. ‘

The Hurricanes have gone 10'

years without a national title and
have run into some troubled times
in recent years, but this year the
fans in Coral Gables have great
hope that Miami will bring home its
. fifth national title this season and

add to the mystique and aura of

